  "061.01.01.01": {
    id: "061.01.01.01",
    text: '\n# Form\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **061.01.01.01.01** -- State that the geoid is an irregular shape based on\n    the surface of the oceans influenced only by gravity and centrifugal force.\n2.  **061.01.01.01.02** -- State that a number of different ellipsoids are used\n    to describe the shape of the Earth for mapping but that WGS-84 is the\n    reference ellipsoid required for geographical coordinates.\n3.  **061.01.01.01.03** -- State that the circumference of the Earth is\n    approximately 40 000 km or approximately 21 600 NM.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 061.01.01.01.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 061.01.01.01.02 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 061.01.01.01.03 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\n### Earth\'s circumference\n\nYou have to remember 2 values: **40 000 km** and **21 600 NM**.\n\nIf you are not keen on memorizing values you should remember that at the equator\n1 minute arc is 1 NM. With 60 minutes in a degree, and 360, you get that\n\n$$\n60 \\times 360 = 21600 minutes = 21600 NM\n$$\n\nYou can then rough estimate `km` from this with the knowledge that\n`1 NM = 1.852km` (you can get this value from your flight computer).\n\n$$\n21600 \\times 1.852 = 40000 km\n$$\n\n<Question id="W2UOXRL0RG" lo={["061.01.01.01.03"]} contentRef="### Earth\'s circumference">\n  <Text variant="oneCorrect">\n    What is, approximately. the circumference of the earth?\n  </Text>\n\n{" "}\n<Option correct why="1 NM = 1 min arc. 60 * 360 = 21 600 = 40 000km">\n  40 000 km\n</Option>\n\n{" "}\n<Option correct why="1 NM = 1 min arc. 60 * 360 = 21 600">\n  21 600 NM\n</Option>\n\n  <Option>40 000 NM</Option>\n  <Option>21 600 km</Option>\n  <Option>20 000 km</Option>\n  <Option>20 000 NM</Option>\n  <Option>80 000 km</Option>\n  <Option>80 000 NM</Option>\n  <Option>43 200 km</Option>\n  <Option>43 200 NM</Option>\n  <Option>15 800 km</Option>\n  <Option>15 800 NM</Option>\n</Question>\n',
    title: "Form",
    questions: [],
    los: ["061.01.01.01.01", "061.01.01.01.02", "061.01.01.01.03"],
  },
  "061.01.01.02": {
    id: "061.01.01.02",
    text: '\n# Earth rotation\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\n1.  **061.01.01.02.01** -- Describe the rotation of the Earth around its own spin\n    axis and the plane of the ecliptic (including the relationship of the spin\n    axis to the plane of the ecliptic).\n2.  **061.01.01.02.02** -- Explain the effect that the inclination of the Earth"s\n    spin axis has on insolation and duration of daylight.\n\n|                 | ATPL(A) | CPL(A) | ATPL(H)/IR | ATPL(H)/VFR | CPL(H) | IR  | CBIR(A) |\n| --------------- | ------- | ------ | ---------- | ----------- | ------ | --- | ------- |\n| 061.01.01.02.01 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n| 061.01.01.02.02 | X       | X      | X          | X           | X      |     |         |\n\n## Summary\n\nThe Artic circle is at 66 degrees 33 minutes North. Higher than this latitude\nduring the Winter months the Sun will not be seen and a state of continuous\nnight or twilight exists.\n\nIf The Sun is at a celestial latitude of 90 degrees then it is directly over the\nsubject\'s head.\\\nThis can occur only within the tropical band of latitude between 23 degrees 27\nminutes North and 23 degrees 27 minutes South\n\n<Question id="UNMI90HZB6" lo={["061.01.01.02.01"]}>\n  <Text variant="oneCorrect">\n    The angle between the plane of the ecliptic and the plane of equator is approximately...\n  </Text>\n\n{" "}\n<Option>27.5</Option>\n<Option>25.3</Option>\n<Option>66.5</Option>\n<Option correct>23.5</Option>\n\n  <Explanation>\n    The ecliptic is the annual path of the apparent Sun around the celestial sphere.\n\n    The Earth\'s vertical axis is tilted by 23 degrees 27 minutes from the vertical.\n\n    A line drawn from the Sun will differ from the plane of the Earth\'s equator by\n    23 degrees 27 minutes.\n\n  </Explanation>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id="UNMI90HZB7" lo={["061.01.01.02.02"]}>\n  <Text variant="oneCorrect">\n    Which is the highest latitude listed below at which the sun will <Subject />?\n  </Text>\n\n{" "}\n<Option>68</Option>\n<Option>72</Option>\n<Option>62</Option>\n<Option>32</Option>\n<Option>21</Option>\n\n{" "}\n<Option\n  why="The Artic / Polar circle is at 66 degrees 33 minutes North / South."\n  definition="rise above the horizon and set every day"\n>\n  66\n</Option>\n\n{" "}\n<Option\n  why="The Artic / Polar circle is at 66 degrees 33 minutes North / South."\n  definition="rise above the horizon and set every day"\n>\n  66.5\n</Option>\n\n  <Option\n    why="The tropic of Cancer / Capricorn is at 23 degrees 25 minutes North / South"\n    subject={[\n    [\n      "reach an altitude of 90 above the horizon at some time during the year",\n    ],\n    ]}\n  >\n    23\n  </Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id="UNMI90HZB4" lo={["061.01.01.02.02"]}>\n  <Text variant="oneCorrect">\n    In which two months of the year is the difference between the transit of the\n    Apparent Sun and Mean Sun across the Greenwich Meridian the greatest?\n  </Text>\n\n  <Option>June and December</Option>\n  <Option>March and September</Option>\n  <Option>April and August</Option>\n  <Option correct>February and November</Option>\n</Question>\n\n<Question id="UNMI90HZB2" lo={["061.01.01.02.02"]}>\n  <Text variant="oneCorrect">Seasons are due to the:</Text>\n  <Option>Earth\'s elliptical orbit around the Sun</Option>\n  <Option correct>inclination of the polar axis with the ecliptic plane</Option>\n  <Option>variable distance between Earth and Sun</Option>\n  <Option>Earth\'s rotation on its polar axis</Option>\n</Question>\n',
    title: "Earth rotation",
    questions: [],
    los: ["061.01.01.02.01", "061.01.01.02.02"],
  },
